          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which head of the quadriceps femoris is unique in also being a flexor of the hip</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which head of the quadriceps femoris is unique in also being a flexor of the hip joint?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vastus lateralis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vastus lateralis originates from the femur and acts only on the knee joint. It cannot flex the hip because it does not cross the hip joint.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vastus medialis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vastus medialis extends the knee and stabilises the patella medially, preventing lateral subluxation. Like the other vasti, it originates from the femur and does not cross the hip.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Rectus femoris</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Rectus femoris originates from the anterior inferior iliac spine and the acetabular rim. Because it crosses both the hip and the knee, it flexes the hip and extends the knee.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Vastus intermedius</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Vastus intermedius lies deep to rectus femoris. It originates from the anterior femoral shaft and acts only on the knee joint.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is rectus femoris. Unlike the three vasti, which originate from the femur, rectus femoris originates from the pelvis — crossing the hip joint — which gives it the additional action of hip flexion."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Rectus femoris is the only bi-articular head of the quadriceps. Its pelvic origin (AIIS and acetabular rim) allows it to flex the hip, while all four heads extend the knee via the common quadriceps tendon."
                }
              ],
