          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>The femoral sheath encloses the femoral artery, vein, and canal. Which major structure of the femoral triangle lies outside this sheath?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Deep inguinal lymph node</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Deep inguinal lymph nodes lie within the femoral canal, which is the most medial compartment of the femoral sheath.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Femoral nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral nerve enters the thigh through the muscular lacuna, lateral to the femoral sheath. It is the only major content of the femoral triangle that lies outside the sheath.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Femoral vein</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral vein lies within the intermediate compartment of the femoral sheath, medial to the femoral artery.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Femoral artery</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The femoral artery occupies the lateral compartment of the femoral sheath. It enters below the inguinal ligament at the midinguinal point.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is the femoral nerve. It enters through the muscular lacuna and lies outside the femoral sheath. The sheath encloses only the femoral artery (lateral compartment), femoral vein (intermediate compartment), and femoral canal with lymphatics (medial compartment)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The femoral nerve enters via the muscular lacuna and lies lateral to the femoral sheath. The sheath only encloses the artery, vein, and canal — structures that pass through the vascular lacuna."
                }
              ],
