          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient develops numbness along the medial side of the leg after great saphenous vein harvesting for coronary artery bypass grafting. Which nerve, travelling through the adductor canal, was most likely injured?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Obturator nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The obturator nerve supplies the medial thigh adductor muscles. It enters via the obturator canal, not the adductor canal, and does not supply the medial leg.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Common peroneal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The common peroneal nerve wraps around the neck of the fibula and supplies the anterolateral leg and dorsum of the foot — not the medial leg.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Saphenous nerve</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The saphenous nerve exits the adductor canal through the vastoadductor membrane and descends with the great saphenous vein along the medial leg. Vein harvesting puts this nerve at risk.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sural nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sural nerve is formed from branches of the tibial and common peroneal nerves behind the knee. It supplies the posterolateral leg and lateral foot.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is the saphenous nerve. It is a purely sensory branch of the femoral nerve that passes through the adductor canal and exits to accompany the great saphenous vein along the medial leg. Its close proximity to the vein makes it vulnerable during harvesting."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The saphenous nerve is the longest cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve. It travels through the adductor canal, exits via the vastoadductor membrane, and accompanies the great saphenous vein — making it vulnerable during vein harvest surgery."
                }
              ],
